Once a cell is run, you naturally want to see the output. If a figure is plotted the output might be off screen and needs to be scrolled into view. This is uncomfortable but can be addressed with overriding the action:

            Jupyter.keyboard_manager.actions.register({
                'help': 'run selected cells',
                'handler': function(env, event) {
                    env.notebook.command_mode();
                    Jupyter.keyboard_manager.actions.call('jupyter-notebook:run-cell', event, env);
                    Jupyter.keyboard_manager.actions.call('jupyter-notebook:scroll-cell-top', event, env);
                    env.notebook.edit_mode();
                }
            }, 'run-cell', '');

However, the scroll-cell-top action will not put the last cell of the notebook at the top because there is no 'content' following and the output the cell produces is not taken into account. And again, you have to scroll down to read the error message or see the output.

Consider an empty notebook with a single empty cell. It's not a problem putting that cell at the top of the page (where else should it be). scroll-cell-top should put a cell at the top, even if it's the bottom cell.

As a developer, I want to copy data to S3 such that the resulting objects are encrypted, so that I can use Odo with sensitive data.

boto's set_contents_from_filename() can take an optional parameter encrypt=True, so there needs to be a way to pass that through the call chain such as append_text_to_s3().

Acceptance criteria:
Save data to S3 in a bucket such that the resulting object is encrypted with AES-256. One way to test this is that a bucket with the following policy, will not allow unencrypted puts:
```
{
   "Version":"2012-10-17",
   "Id":"PutObjPolicy",
   "Statement":[{
         "Sid":"DenyUnEncryptedObjectUploads",
         "Effect":"Deny",
         "Principal":"*",
         "Action":"s3:PutObject",
         "Resource":"arn:aws:s3:::mybucket/*",
         "Condition":{
            "StringNotEquals":{
               "s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption":"AES256"
            }
         }
      }
   ]
}
```

